The Ukrainian parliament today refused the request to abolish the paragraphs on the basis of which the opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko had been convicted, as part of a amendment to the Penal Code.
The new regulation, which could have paved the way for the release of the imprisoned Minister of Expression, was rejected by MEPs at the second reading of the motion for a reduction in penalties for economic offences.
Timoshenko was sentenced in October to seven years in prison for concluding an allegedly detrimental contract with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not yet final, the appeal of the convicted will be tried in court in December.
Timoshenko himself described the verdict as a political revenge of the regime and also in the West, the process raised the suspicion of the court’s bias.
The request to remove paragraph 365, on the basis of which the Minister of Expression was sentenced, from the Criminal Code, was supported by 147 deputies.
226 votes would have been required for its adoption.
