The menu of an obese child: it does not eat breakfast and eats sausage for dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with being overweight, with 9 percent of all students and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Recent surveys have shown that obese children are mostly from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This shows once again how important the environment in which a person grows and the examples that surround him is for the healthy development of a person.
On the tables of obese children, sausages are up to half more often on the table than in families where normal-weight children live.
More than 19 percent of overweight children had fries for dinner on the day before the education campaign under the motto "obesity is not a coincidence".
In families with thick children, sport is not exactly one of the favorite occupations, but what also affects the majority of today's students - only 15 percent replied that their parents find time for active exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place towards the end of the school year last year, with nearly 900 children from primary schools across the Czech Republic being surveyed.
This was already the second year of the "Adiposity is not a coincidence" campaign, which is supported by the General Health Insurance and the company Unilever.
To date, more than 12 thousand students from 4th and 8th grades have participated in the project.
Unhealthy eating and lack of exercise in the family are crucial factors that are responsible for the frighteningly increasing number of children with overweight or even obesity.
“For example, only half of the children surveyed said they ate breakfast-second breakfast-lunch-vesser-evening bread five times a day – one of the main prerequisites for a healthy diet,” according to one of the survey results.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that even relative small things, such as the regular breakfast time of the family, are important for the healthy development of a child.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of the families of students eat breakfast.
And - in most families, everyone eats breakfast on their own.
Worst of all, one in ten families doesn’t eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
The survey test revealed, among other things, that in the families of overweight children, unhealthy fries are consumed much more often.
And almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet sodas every day (70 percent)
Although more than 40 percent of the children surveyed exercise, only less than half of their parents do – only 15 percent.
Make your own menu
A further part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to compile their own diet from the options offered according to appetite and opinion.
“What Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15 prefer in terms of nutrition is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among her favorite dishes were many flours, meat dishes and, of course, sweets.
"Alarming is above all the great popularity of sweet sodas," the final report on this survey stresses.
At lunch, i.e. the main dish, dough products won just before poultry.
The children almost did not like legumes and also the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes as lunch was very low.
Back to health
At the same time, the survey also showed that children are quite willing to change their eating habits if they get the right information.
"In the control group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the conclusion of the enlightening lecture 'Obesity is not a coincidence', there was in many cases a significant shift in preferences towards principles of healthy eating," the results of the project said.
This was evident, for example, in the sweet limos, where many children began to give priority to ordinary water.
The children also crossed poultry or fish much more often in the questionnaire as the main dish of the day and were willing to eat less dumplings or sweet food.
