V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Rezension
The originally carefree ride is made by a series of completely avoidable, dilettantic mistakes to the routine ride to the early shift.
Although it has succeeded in fulfilling the ambitions to a large extent, but what good is it if obviously no one wanted to do a little more.
Even before it came to the tables, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" aroused high expectations.
He promised to move the already aged "Need for Speed" game series back to a new dimension and in the playable demonstration examples he actually seemed to be not just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious about the passages where the main protagonist gets out of the car and walks on.
But as you’re used to at NFS, in the end it’s a lot different than you expected.
Sure - potentially it's quite decent arcade races, but overall the game is diminished by some superfluous mistakes that have been present in this series for more or less a few years.
So they are actually no longer mistakes, but rather signs of a basically incomprehensible laziness of the game developers.
The adventure starts very well.
For the first time, one is introduced to the story, whose main character Jack has certain personal problems; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, on the west coast, you sit at the wheel - with the task of being the first in New York.
The basic idea includes a number of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is held on another track and that the individual stages take place in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
You don’t have the impression that the game will always offer the same thing.
Some environments are still quite beautiful to look at, although the technical level of the graphics does not go beyond that of the previous parts of the series.
So nothing world-moving.
But driving through the desert, through autumn landscape or high up through deep snowy landscape seems visually very pleasant.
Every now and then, unusual elements bring a little variety to the individual races.
In the desert, for example, you are surprised by a desert storm that severely restricts the view.
In the mountains, in turn, you have to be hellishly careful not to be spilled by an avalanche.
By the way, the individual races are built in quite a succession.
Only a few, but they are enough.
For a while you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to catch up (classic race against the stopwatch), then there is another personal duel with a single opponent.
And the police, who want to mess up the whole thing.
A novelty are passages in which Jack leaves the car.
It is more about certain interactive animations in which Jack escapes from anyone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
However, it is surprising that there are far fewer such passages in the game than you would expect (perhaps only three).
Ultimately, this is more to the advantage of the game, because this element at least has no chance of getting boring - it belongs in the context of the aforementioned elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of the previous parts.
That is, from the point of view of today, it does not tear out trees, on the other hand, one could not say that it would be bad.
If you are looking for realistic simulations, you have to look elsewhere.
But for action-packed racing, the local driving model is still quite good, although you could find better in the competition.
Until then, everything is in the best order.
Real problems only appear after a certain period of time.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not quite OK.
From a game of this kind it is hardly expected that it calculates complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have practically no idea before any impact on any object how the car behaves, then obviously not everything is fine.
Typical example: When narrowly overtaking or passing by oncoming cars, in some places you "strip" the other car only easily, but in others, almost identical situations, you get into a sling and spin wild pirouettes.
Or drive the car to scrap.
Thanks to the restart system, this does not matter any more, but it is always annoying.
The restarts are solved: if you have total damage or land far off the track, then the game throws you back to the last point of the track.
Only - in each race you only have five restarts.
Once you've exhausted them, everything goes from scratch.
So the restarts are more like a tool, in case something does not succeed, but you should not rely on it.
Sometimes, however, the restart does not even help, there is nothing else than learning the critical section from the head.
It is very unpleasant that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, you have to go through some corners in a very specific way, otherwise you just don't fit through.
Elsewhere, "civil" cars are always in the same configuration, whether you arrive first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations when you see the opponent passing two cars in front of you, but by the time you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive them around or brake them.
And it doesn’t matter when you get there, because everything is designed so that this situation always comes close to your nose.
The opponents have other advantages.
Throughout the game there are a few places where you are always overtaken by the same opponent in the same place and again here regardless of the timing.
At the craziest, this is the end of the game on the long bridge that you pass in the opposite direction.
The opponent has to overtake one here obviously on devil come out.
And if he is in front of you, then of course he takes your sight away, so that you drive your own car a few times in Klump at the beginning.
Sure - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting, but this intention is so clear that it quickly misses the joy of the game.
And that’s a pity, because despite the simpler driving model, the game is quite entertaining and sometimes so full of action that you almost don’t know where your head is.
And in principle, it doesn’t matter what “fault” it is – the concept with fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in a way that no boredom can arise, or something completely different...
An unusual idea is also the change of cars during the races.
You should not overlook the petrol stations on the track, because it is here that you can change the car, although in most cases the car you have just is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for the urban areas, the strong American limousines for the straight highways and exotic super sports cars for the technical rides, for example on the mountain serpentines.
Goes hand in hand with the game story mode also the task mode (challenges) - that is, the races in the individual locations that you know from the story.
There are not only medals here, but also experience points for your own profile, which is common for the tasks (challenges) and the story.
To reach the higher driver level, different items must be opened up: from the car to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is at the same time connected to the online function Autolog, which among other things compares the results achieved with those of other players and also provides more collective functions.
Another incomprehensible carver is a situation in the last race of history.
Here you can get by car into a subway tunnel (my way), where you can race long on the rails (my way) in the dark.
On the speedometer, numbers look between 150 and 200 km/h (my way), but there comes suddenly a subway from behind and drives an uncompromising to scrap.
In our editorial we will probably argue for a long time about whether this was a blackout of the game designers or whether the authors think we are so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the overall visual impression is quite appealing in most cases and here and there even brilliant.
All the more annoying is that at some exciting moments, the refresh rate slows down and this is sometimes quite dramatic.
However, this applies in particular to accidents involving a greater number of participants, where a continuous FPS is of no use anyway.
The sound playback is OK and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to appeal to as wide a scale as possible rather young audiences, a soundtrack a l<0xC3><0xA0> "of everyone something" was created - but who buys such a game because of the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run? The feelings are rather mixed.
If the game were not diminished by the totally unnecessary mistakes mentioned, we would have been able to claim with the breast tone of conviction that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But that's how the game somehow looks unfinished.
In itself a great pleasure, but you should be prepared for these mistakes with the power of airport headlights to catch your eye.
