Innovator IBM enters the second century of its existence
If you wanted to look for a suitable word that most accurately characterizes IBM’s strategy, then that would probably be the word “longevity”.
For the general public, IBM is synonymous with technological revolution, it is known as a modern company, although a century has passed since its foundation.
The foundation for this longevity has already been laid by their first boss - the visionary Thomas J. Watson sen.
Already he advocated the slogan, countless worldwide problems could be easily solved if people were willing to think a bit.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the trademark for the life of the future giant (and at the same time the title of the company's in-house magazine, which began to be published at IBM in 1935).
This was also the basis of Watsen’s well-prepared corporate culture.
“For us at IBM, this long-term thinking represents a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and succeeded for an entire century because it remained true to its principles and did not shy away from changing everything else around.
This allowed us to transform technologies, business and society during our first century.
We hope that we will achieve even more in the next hundred years,” said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company’s current director for the anniversary.
Well-thought-out system
In the 1930s, Watson worked as a social care worker in the same way as the entrepreneur Ba<0xC5><0xA5>a in Czechoslovakia: the IBM people were one of the first American employees to have paid vacation, insurance from the entrepreneur plus elegant uniforms as workwear and a well-thought-out pay system for the best innovators and traders.
IBM’s long-term relationships with its customers are equally sophisticated.
