His best-known inventions include, for example, ATMs, credit cards, financial swap, bar code or the floppy disk.
At approximately $220 billion in market capitalization, IBM was the second-largest technology company this year (after Apple), overtaking Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
Looking ahead
Not all products and innovations met the taste of today's customers - unfortunate were, for example, the attempt with its own OS/2, the online service Prodigy or the computers IBM PC jr.
"Business is based on the forward movement, so you should not be emotionally attached to the past," says Samuel J. Palmisano.
That’s why IBM has no problem building its foundations on various platforms — and if they don’t work, leaving them again.
In contrast to the opponent Microsoft, which in principle stands and falls with its operating system Windows.
Promising technologies for success
IBM’s profits account for the largest share of services, software and hardware, each one-fifth.
In 1990, hardware was the most represented, with a share of more than fifty percent.
Since 2000, IBM has sold little profitable assets worth $15 billion, but at the same time it has invested $58 billion in the purchase of promising technologies.
In these investments, IBM continues even after 2008, when the modern financial crisis swept the world like a storm for the first time.
Here, too, IBM remained faithful to the legacy of its first chief Thomas J. Watson, who increased its investment scope in the midst of the great global economic crisis.
So far, it seems that the company IBM survives the current crisis unaffected.
The value of IBM shares has increased by 120 percent since 2008 and the company’s net profit is growing continuously.
IBM’s corporate slogan is: Everything can be changed – only the values cannot be changed.
This flexible giant can also be expected to cope with the next crisis.
IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Spaceflights
Founded one hundred years ago in New York, IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It wasn’t until 1924 that the company took the name IBM – originally a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation for the later company IBM was laid by the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 1980s.
They possessed technologies such as the famous punch card clocks for registering the beginning and end of work.
The architect of this new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who was also chairman of the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the head of the competing company Thomas J. Watson to help him run the company.
This leader even overshadowed IBM’s founders – Watson’s ideas are based on the company’s invincible culture and identity to this day.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM began, as the name suggests, with the production and distribution of all kinds of machines for the trade - from sausage and cheese cutters to checkouts.
In the first four decades that Watson led the company, he doubled his revenues to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the chief chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM’s technicians and computers helped direct NASA’s flights into space – to Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969 also to man’s famous flight to the moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers with the same computer architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC, which set the computer standard of that time, was launched in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it bought the consulting part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus fully entered the business of consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the past three years is the “Smarter Planet” concept.
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in areas not even planned until now, e.g. to improve the situation in traffic and city administration.
In the commerce sector, IBM recently introduced the “Smarter Commerce” platform, which is designed to help traders guide the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
In 1932, IBM established a branch in Czechoslovakia, the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM <0xC4><0x8C>R also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central and Eastern European Headquarters is located in Prague and is also home to a world-class research team dedicated to the technology of voice recognition.
