Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five approved state travel agencies in the former <0xC4><0x8C>SSR: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies at that time mainly sold only trips to the socialist Eastern Bloc countries, in the West at that time only chosen ones were allowed.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimea peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A clear exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when travel to Yugoslavia was also allowed, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of socialist times was that even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (i.e. Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely within the framework of socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the <0xC4><0x8C>SSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed an so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual trips were not possible.
Already at that time the travel agencies also offered trips to the West, but then you had to buy huge snakes or stay in a sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
This was not the case for a long time.
The so-called foreign exchange commitment - the condition for an exit to the West - was only granted to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without currency commitment it would have been impossible to raise the necessary financial resources (western currency) for a trip to the West.
As a result, most of the Czechs spent their holidays in the Czech Republic, it is no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dates - a habit that continues to this day.
The Velvet Revolution of 1989 was followed by a travel revolution of the Czechs.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox, of which one is no longer aware today, is the fact that one could not travel to the currently most popular holiday country of the Czechs - Croatia until 1989 at all, because it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 90s of the last century, the foreign exchange obligation in the neighboring Western European countries was abolished, which caused a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and to Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of their travels to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to be there at least a few days.
For example, the Czech holidaymakers slept in the tent in the park when they traveled to Paris, because who would have already had the money for an accommodation in a hotel or a pension at the time.
A typical feature of foreign travel in the Czech Republic was a trunk packed with canned beer, permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our standard of living and thus also the average salaries increased, which led to another important moment in 1997.
Due to the increased demand for travel, after 1997, travel agencies began to regularly prepare travel through charter flights, making air travel unbelievably cheaper than in the past thanks to the possibility of negotiating bulk discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the US, already had currencyless payments with all the advanced countries of the world, which made travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-samtenen" travel came in 2000, when, thanks to high demand, the first direct charter flight to an exotic country - to Thailand - was made.
Since then, direct charter planes with Czech passengers have flown to far-flung sunny countries every year; this year, twelve exotic destinations are to be flown directly from the Czech Republic.
The Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another significant moment in the epoch that marked our “post-revolutionary” development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad for the first time (50.3%) and for the first time in their history spent more than CZK 15 thousand per capita on a single holiday, including the cost of the resort.
