However, the building was neither spatially nor technically suitable as a museum - no walls for hanging art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art in Vienna got a new home.
Since 2001, the building has been empty and has come down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21er Haus" and will be used in the future as a museum for contemporary art.
On Tuesday evening, the Belvedere Museum, to which the house belongs, opens its first exhibition - a chance in every respect.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Belvedere Gallery in 2007, has succeeded the new beginning.
Husslein-Arco, a doctorate in art historian with a considerable career, among other things in the youth as an ice skater, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, strongly enforced the conversion among politicians and protectors of monuments, she procured public funds and private sponsorship funds and put the use into practice.
In addition to present-day art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba should be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, there should be a café and a bookshop, and an office building had to be built for this purpose.
Strict supervision, small budget
Krischanitz was the ideal cast for the performance.
Not only because he had sensitively rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich’s Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied at Schwanzer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was an “uniquely important place” for him, where he had watched the exhibitions “almost every weekend”.
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which already lost in generosity and ease when it was moved to Vienna and its reuse.
During the current renovation, there were much bigger problems: the building was "an energy spinner", says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade were replaced, glass-fiber-reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold bridge steel supports have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been refurbished.
Two basements brought space for the new use, a lowered moat of light between the house and the street provides for the exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light tail pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in old red-brown anti-rust shade.
And the cinema is still exactly as it used to be.
And all this under strict supervision of the monumental authority and with a small budget.
"Often a material had to be found that is good and cheap and also appealed to the Heritage Office," says Krischanitz, pointing to a rugged floor in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and modifications, the building has remained flexible and light.
