Since then, the Chairman of the Board of Directors of UBS has also been considered a hit man - and everyone asks: When will Axel Weber finally arrive?
It has already been announced that Weber will be able to advise the bank from February 2012.
And he is already taking over the chairmanship of the board of directors in May - not only in 2013, as the bank announced on Tuesday.
For Axel Weber, this is going to be hard.
He is not a banker, but rather an economics professor and central banker and would certainly have needed a training period.
He then takes responsibility for the strategy of a bank that has just proved once again that it has long since earned the title of "Europe's largest scandal bank".
Because UBS is huge on the one hand - until recently it was the largest asset manager in the world - and on the other hand has been slipping from one scandal to the next for years.
Nothing, it seems, is spared the once so proud Swiss bank.
It began in the financial crisis.
Until 2007, UBS had an excellent reputation.
She had combined the image of the hidden and solid but also exhausted Swiss asset manager with ambitious goals: she also wanted to become a very large number in investment banking.
In 2007, UBS managed $1.6 trillion more money from wealthy customers than any other bank in the world.
And on the other hand, it was advanced as an investment bank into the league of the largest banks in the world.
It made an impression.
Hans Geiger, a former banker and a long-time banking professor in Zurich, said: “I have always portrayed UBS as a model of a good bank for my students at the time.”
“From today’s point of view, you ask yourself: How could I be so wrong?”
He was very wrong.
In 2007, it became apparent for the first time that something was going wrong in UBS.
In the middle of the year, CEO Peter Wuffli resigned surprisingly, who until then was considered a highly intellectual and equally ingenious banker.
A few months later, they knew why he had left.
The bank’s investment division had been rigged with subprime papers and had to write off billions.
To support this, UBS announced a capital increase of a whopping 13 billion francs.
For this, she did find investors, but those, over which some until a short while ago had still had the nose: an intransparent Asian State Fund from Singapore and an Arab State Fund, which was so silent that one did not even know his name.
But that was only the first blow.
In April 2008, it was worse.
The bank had to announce new billions of losses, Chairman Marcel Ospel, still the second-highest-paid board of directors in Switzerland, resigned in 2006.
In October 2008, the catastrophe ensued: UBS stood before the collapse in the face of its misinvestments in the financial crisis and had to be rescued by the state.
The National Bank bought UBS for tens of billions of problematic securities, the Swiss Confederation gave six billion francs for a forced-change bond through which it could become co-owner of the bank.
The whole of Switzerland was shaken - because she noticed how dramatic it is for a small country to host such large banks.
Finally, the balance sheet total of UBS 2007 was more than five times the economic performance of Switzerland (see chart).
“We couldn’t save UBS again,” says bank researcher Geiger.
The first disaster was followed by the second.
Only a few months later, UBS capitulated in the tax dispute with America and agreed to release the data of wealthy customers who may have defrauded taxes with the help of the bank.
In addition, it agreed to a payment of $780 million - in repayment of unjustified profits from these transactions, including a penalty charge.
Thus, the UBS more or less openly acknowledged that it had helped with tax evasion.
At the same time, she lost something that had always been her capital in competition for rich customers: the nimbus of secrecy.
After the scandal, the Swiss banking secret was no longer the same.
This was followed by the resignation of the Chief Executive Officer and Chairman of the Board of Directors.
And the exodus of customer money.
Within a few months, the bank had lost its credibility in both core business areas: investment banking through misspeculation and asset management through aid for tax evasion.
And just as it got a little quieter again, just when you thought that UBS would get it back, this unfortunate trader story follows: A single trader cheats 1.7 billion euros before the bank realizes that something is going wrong.
And it will become apparent: with risk management in investment banking, it obviously still does not work.
"With the Adoboli case, we have to find that risk control has changed too little," says Martin Janssen, economist and financial professor at the Bank Institute of the University of Zurich.
The chief financial officer of a large German bank is also sure: "The problem with UBS is that it does not have risk control under control."
It was precisely the idea of caution with which the Swiss bankers had long ago begun to become guardians of the world’s great assets: no too great risks, but security for money – even beyond the Alpine Republic the world might collapse.
The safes of the Swiss banks had become a symbol of unwavering reliability, like Lindt and Sprüngli for particularly noble chocolate.
The head office of UBS in Zurich still fits the cliché of the well-deserved Swiss private bank - it is only a little larger.
Already the location is classic.
The bank is headquartered on Zurich’s Bahnhofstraße, which leads directly from the main station to Lake Zurich, which is surrounded by the snow-capped peaks of the Swiss mountains.
The buildings here are magnificent, the shop rentals are among the highest in Europe.
Jewelers like Tiffany's can be found here among traditional Swiss shops such as the Confiserie Sprüngli.
Swiss banks have resided here for centuries: from the National Bank to the Palace of Credit Suisse to elite private banks such as Julius Baer.
The reception hall of the UBS is entered through a heavy revolving door.
Inside the walls are marble-clad, in front of them are thick leather armchairs, next to the bank logo a large sign for the "safe".
UBS knows what the customer is looking for here: security.
This idea of the Swiss bank has both large Swiss banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, but eventually displaced - or betrayed, as the head of a small Swiss private bank finds.
He prefers not to read his name in the newspaper, after all, like all Swiss bankers, he also does business with the two big banks.
The UBS has become much too large, he finds - especially in investment banking, where also the Anglo-Saxons would have spread.
The Swiss have nothing more to say.
"And if so, they have long since adapted to the customs of the Anglo-Saxons."
In fact, it was Anglo-Saxon investment banking that changed UBS, gave it high profits and then the debacle: no European financial institution has lost as much money in the subprime jungle as the Swiss major bank.
On October 15, 2008, the disaster became visible.
"On that Wednesday, the coalition government of the small seven-million country decided the largest rescue operation in the history of their nation," writes author Lukas Hässig in his book "The UBS Crash".
Up to 68 billion francs or around 45 billion euros were granted by the politicians to save the bank from bankruptcy.
How could this have happened?
If you talk to Swiss bankers, they see the problem above all in the size of UBS.
In June 1998, two of the three major Swiss banks merged into a huge group.
A bank was created that was already too big for the small Switzerland at the time of the merger - and was growing ever further.
The two different predecessor banks of UBS complemented each other: a rich but sleepy bank with a focus on asset management in Zurich and a poorer but already more internationalized one.
Suddenly the internationalized investment bankers came in favor of a lot of money, with which they could spin a huge wheel.
Two names are associated with this rise of UBS: Peter Wuffli, Group CEO of UBS from 2001 to 2007, and Marcel Ospel, then Chairman of the Board of Directors.
“I always thought Wuffli and Ospel were a dream team,” says bank researcher Hans Geiger.
"Wuffli, the high-intellectual, modest, who understands a lot about models and statistics, and Ospel, the abdominal man who has worked himself up from banking to the very top."
But Ospel finally relied on Wuffli.
And Wuffli probably made a decisive mistake in the end: "He thought his models were the reality," Geiger says.
“This is a tragic case.”
Tragic, perhaps.
Obviously, arrogance came before the case.
UBS employees clearly remember the executive meetings at which Group CEO Wuffli repeated the same slogan: Throwing Goldman Sachs from the throne.
The American bank was the most powerful investment bank in the world.
She led the League Tables, the rankings that documented the success of the banks of that time.
That’s where the UBS wanted to go, to the top.
A few steps have already been taken.
In foreign exchange and stock trading, she played at the very top.
However, business consultants, who were commissioned, highlighted a weakness: in the international interest rate business, in the banker's language "fixed income", there is a huge distance to the largest banks.
UBS has gaps in American mortgage products.
To close this gap, UBS embarked on an adventure that almost cost it its existence.
Hungry for growth, both the bank itself and a hedge fund founded before it invested in American subprime investments.
It developed into a huge machine that packaged and passed on securities on American mortgage loans - but also kept risks on its own.
Also, when other banks have long sought the exit.
“Even in the summer of 2007, when the American real estate market was on fire, UBS bought there,” says bank expert Geiger.
So great the euphoria, so deep the case.
One manager after another had to leave when the attempts to clean up were more difficult than expected.
Positions at UBS have become a spinning seat and are shaky to this day.
Whoever runs the big bank now has an almost impossible job.
He must find a strategy for a bank that has lost all related business models.
Bank researcher Geiger already has an idea: stop investing, focus on asset management, return to Swiss roots.
The bank does not (yet) want to go that far.
But investment banking is to shrink sharply, so much is already clear.
On Thursday, Sergio Ermotti will present his future strategy to the world.
The 51-year-old Italo-Swiss was actually only intended as a transitional solution when the bank surprisingly separated from its predecessor Grübel.
In the meantime, he has prevailed: he is to permanently run the business of UBS, the Zurich Bank announced on Tuesday.
Ermotti wants the investment bank to return to mid-nineties.
He cut 3,500 jobs.
But that won't suffice.
UBS needs a vision.
Who is she?
What does she want to make money with?
These are the questions that Axel Weber is sure to ask himself now.
So far, he only says publicly that he will first look for an apartment in Zurich with his wife.
Next year.
