Smart crows spread in cities
In many places, seed crows are considered "problem birds": but the highly intelligent animals can no longer be driven out of the cities, experts claim.
Some like it, others want to get rid of it very quickly: crows have been part of the cityscape for centuries, but in many municipalities local complaints about dirt and noise of animals pile up.
So far, a remedy against the “problem birds” is not in sight.
Seed crows can no longer be obtained from the cities, experts said at the first crow symposium in the East Frisian Leer.
There, experts from all over the federal territory discussed possible solutions.
You are looking for alternatives in the cities
Conservationists also attributed the problems in cities to the escape of specially protected seed crows: the use of chemicals in agriculture is increasingly destroying traditional habitats.
The hunting, increasing cultivation and the fall of typical breeding trees made life difficult for the birds.
Crows are protected.
There are large colonies with more than 600 breeding pairs in the Westphalian Soest, in the northwest among others in Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen as well as in Leer.
There, in 2005, a controversial project for the mass killing of crows in the county had caused negative headlines.
Critics had described the catching of the animals in bird traps and the killing with sticks as particularly brutal.
"The normal expulsion, the burying, does nothing," said the city and landscape planner Werner Klöver from Leer.
Nests spraying away with water or cutting down trees often have undesirable consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser from Lahr in Baden-Württemberg.
“Animals are escaping, large colonies are splitting up and dispersing in other places.”
Burial is only conceivable as an exception in hospitals, retirement homes or schools.
“We have to live with them, we can’t get them away anymore.”
Without the surrounding area, the problem could not be solved in the cities, said Mayor Wolfgang Kellner from Leer.
A combination of burying the animals from sensitive living areas and locking offers to resettle them in other places is conceivable.
On the other hand, the psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jürgens called for a completely different way of dealing with the animals: "We can finally endure a pimple in the face with confidence."
Jürgens had co-founded in Schleswig-Holstein the Ascheberger Krähen-Lehrpfad, where signs inform about the lives of the highly intelligent seed crows.
The project is already being accepted by tourists.
Jürgens also had his own opinion about the noise of birds: "There is a lot of communication, they have a lot to say."
The intelligence and skill of the animals are legendary: not only do seed crows use tools to get to a treat, but they even make their own tools as tools.
Behavioural researchers at the University of Cambridge recently tested on four seed crows how far the intelligence of the birds goes.
In one experiment, the birds quickly learned that they had to bring down a scaffold with stones in order to reach a moth larva.
Without much training, they determined what size and shape a stone must have in order for the platform to collapse.
In a second attempt, the clever crows had to solve a more tricky problem.
In a vertically positioned cylinder, the researchers had placed a small bucket with a moth larvae.
With the beak the birds could not reach their prey.
However, the researchers had laid them wire pieces.
From this all four animals formed a hook, with the help of which they then fished the bucket at the handle from the tube.
Three of the four seed crows even managed to do this right away.
