Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Watch You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just one of many guys who sent their anti-immigration opinion online.
On Monday, Breivik, who confessed to having committed a shooting in Norway in July in which 77 people were killed, had his first public hearing in court.
Although Breivik may have acted alone, he is far from alone in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time before his attack on his computer and chatted with some of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on social networking sites.
After the tragedy of this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
This is easy - you only have to log in to Facebook.
“We found it wasn’t hard to get to them,” says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report by the British idea factory DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook’s hiding of personal data is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers simply have to use the site’s advertising tool to accurately define their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy – just as marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of far-right groups across Europe and then targeted them with adds, but instead of linking to a new band or diet product, the adds invited users to a survey asking about their educational status, attitude to violence, and assessment of their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – without even having to leave their office once.
“It’s a fairly new research method,” Bartlett says.
Online supporters of far-right groups are mostly young, male, and upset about immigration.
“Those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who sit behind their computer screens.”
DEMO’s work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Idea factories, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to societal trends such as "likes", text messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding on average three content per day, Facebook’s “data supernova” is generating a research boom that has increased the number of scientific papers with that page’s name in the title by nearly 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that you can study people through this site that you don’t usually reach with your clipboard on the street.
“If you used to try to interview people of the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them.”
“They had to inform the party first and it would never have granted them access,” Bartlett says.
“At Facebook, it all goes away – you go straight to them.”
Others say that the site offers a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their total intoxication on Facebook are significantly more likely to have problems with drinking than students who were silent about the topic.
Moreno suggests that peer students, such as residential consultants, monitor the site and help a student if it posts too many status updates.
“You can’t solve a problem if you haven’t recognized it,” Dimitri Christakis, Morenos co-author and head of Child Health, Behavior and Development at Children’s Research Institute in Seattle, told the Washington Post.
"We have found a way to identify vulnerable children who would not otherwise have been found."
Facebook is also constantly retrieving the data of its own population.
The site’s data team has compiled statistics on relationship status and Valentine’s Day, voter turnout in the 2010 midterm elections, and a National Happiness Index (which primarily used data that only Facebook has access to – masters of digital freedom have long known that the site should make its large data trove accessible to others for research purposes.)
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they want it or not. To be able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the site is allowed to display its own personal data.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know about?
While researchers have strict guidelines on how to collect their data offline, anything is allowed online.
“I don’t think many users have thought at all about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, to a 2006 study in which he examined the public pages of students on Facebook.
"As for her, it was just about her and her friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research participant is absolutely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how much of the information in a user profile and in posts is true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn says.
Therefore, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn thinks that a clipboard and a pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
“There’s no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people,” he says.
“Social research needs to take care of the social – and a lot of social life is still taking place offline.”
