7 Lessons From The Interview With Deceased Steve Jobs Showed In A Theater This Week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, highlighting the engineering genius as a great modern inventor.
But what Apple fans may find most revealing in the recently re-discovered job interview, which was dusted off this week before special film screenings in the major markets, is how much this creative head has understood business processes and workflows.
He was certainly a designer, a dreamer, and self-appointed hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer who was eager to craft diagrams - a man who believed that many CEOs suffer from "a disease of thought," "that a really great idea makes up 90 percent of the work... [but] there's an enormous amount of craftsmanship between a great product and a great idea."
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the TV series "Triumph of the Idiots" about the departure of the personal computer, and he sat with jobs for more than an hour, in which they had one of the rare, detailed conversations.
By this time, it had been more than 10 years since jobs had been pushed out of Apple, and he was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, looking forward to the widespread adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringley’s interview was used in specialist idiots, he says that the copy templates of the interview were missing at delivery.
It was only after Jobs’ death that a full VHS copy was discovered in the director’s garage.
This slightly overhauled footage forms the basis for the 68-minute film "Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview", which comes to the Landmark Theater this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known for hating detailed interviews, Jobs appears surprisingly eager to explain his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
In the course of the interview, there are four times longer pauses between question and answer - 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, in which Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts and strives for accuracy.
There are also moments when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to light when he seemingly impatiently responds to Cringely’s questions and prompts him to respond more quickly to issues or side actions of greater importance.
Before the era of Pixar, iPod, or iPhone, the Lost Interview appears somewhat eeriely farsighted when jobs evaluate what other companies do right or wrong in his opinion and represent his own vision for the future of the computer.
It's one thing to read posthumously honoring Jobs' career, but to see Jobs here as the eager dreamer on the leap to grandeur is something completely different, original and inspiring.
He has a vision of how things could and should be.
Shortly after he had done all this here, he went off and did it.
A quick look at seven remarkable sequences of the Lost Interview:
How he learned to run a company:
"Throughout the years in business, I always ask, 'Why do you do things?' And the answer you always get is, 'Oh, that's how it's done.'
Nobody knows why he does what he does, nobody in business really thinks about things.
That's what I've noticed.
Jobs continues his efforts to streamline accounting at Apple.
Astonished at how costs were recorded – usually starting with “standard costs” based on mere guesswork and then adjusted with “deviation” – he developed an automated factory that ensured that business costs could be determined to the smallest extent.
How the pope was deceived:
Jobs tells of the "Blue Box", which he built with Steve Wozniak, a device with which you could sneak into the telephone company and have long distance conversations for free.
A lot has been written about the device, but Jobs’ enthusiasm when he describes the Blue Box as an act of self-empowerment is contagious.
He describes how Wozniak and he would test the box by using a pay phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another as they grind through as many satellites as possible.
“We sent stuff around the globe half a dozen times, and when you groaned on the phone, it came out a minute later on the phone next door,” Jobs says.
“We were young and we learned that we can build something ourselves that can control trillions of dollars in infrastructure around the world.”
We both didn’t know much, but we were able to build this little thing that can control a gigantic thing, that was an incredible lesson and I don’t think there would be Apple without it.
Jobs continues to talk about a glorious prank that Wozniak and he had almost pulled off when they called in the middle of the night via Blue Box in the Vatican and wanted to talk to the Pope while they were as good as they could to imitate Henry Kissinger.
Since several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the American diplomat, the two had to laugh before the pope himself came on the phone.
How he fell in love with technology (and unpreparedly called Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, when he was looking for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he searched for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after her 20-minute phone call, Jobs got a part-time job for the summer at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had a remarkable impact on me; it was the only company I had seen at that age and it formed my views on what a company was and how well it treated its employees."
Later, Jobs became one of the HP employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever made.”
It was as big as a suitcase, had a small screen with Braunscher tube and I fell in love with it.
I would climb up at HP as a teenager and hang on to this machine and write programs for it.
How to improve innovation:
Several times in the interview, Jobs talks about how to spontaneously invent new products.
Early in his career, when he installed some boards, he was asked by a customer to assemble the entire computer.
He worked with a payment period of only 30 days and had to think through both the assembly and the delivery of the finished equipment.
Later at Apple, he recalls the problems he had in developing a computer mouse:
“I remember sweeping arguments... they yelled at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300] and I got up, went out and found a manufacturer.”
Ninety days later we had a mouse that we could build for $15, which was incredibly credible.
About large companies that are declining:
Long before he resurrected Apple, Jobs foresaw the ways in which so many industrial giants stumbled with their visions and lost control of their stocks.
“Let’s say you work at IBM or Xerox, so make a better copier or printer, okay?”
They own the stock monopoly, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [are those people] who ultimately run the companies and the product that pushes people out of decision-making.
The product genius that has led to this monopoly position is being eradicated by people who have no concept regarding good products vs. bad products - craftsmanship.
This happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times bigger if Microsoft had been in the 1990s.
You have taken the defeat of victory.
About innovation as an art form:
“There’s a lot of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product... when you develop this great idea, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about his intricacies.
You have to make votes, certain things that you can't do, but electrons, glass, robots, factories.
You have to remember 5000 things, these concepts, and bring them all together...
Ultimately, it comes down to the taste, it comes down to trying to deal with the best stuff that humans have created, and then trying to bring those things together to what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We are always shameless in stealing great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh great was that the people who worked there were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians who happened to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it hadn’t been the computer industry, they would have done fantastic things in other areas.
