How to unmask a lie
A look at the current headlines shows how troubling and widespread deception and lies are in daily life.
The Republican presidential candidate, Herman Cain, is busy dealing with accusations of sexual harassment by several women, both accusing each other of lying.
The Penn State administration is accused of perjury for allegedly withholding reports that a retired football coach sexually abused boys.
Last week, an open microphone was heard when French President Nikolas Sarkozy claimed to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weidner made a fool of himself when he circulated denials that were quickly disproved by indisputable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards is accused of breaches in campaign funding related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And then, of course, no one who has experienced it forgets the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered when he lied during his second term at the Oval Office about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Stories about cheating in school and at college exams are widespread.
There have been incidents where teachers have given their students the test responses so that they are doing well even in their performance checks.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lies and cheating are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
Studies show that we lie between 10 and 200 times a day.
However, many of these lies are considered emergency lies.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Recognizing or "discovering lies" is one that is important to learn for every person, and this for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from a social game such as Sharades, in which the goal is to call out “have you!”, the unmasking of a deception is a reputable area of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that have carried out far-reaching research projects, especially in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most ancient myths about lying have been exposed.
Lies look you in the eye.
They stutter, stammer, blush and twitch not always.
However, it cannot be concluded from this that these liars are difficult to uncover and unmask.
A trained liar can penetrate to the truth by learning about the structure of the claim, the fine facial expressions, about questioning and timing.
I have spent several years examining the scientific results of the extensive and ever-growing area of debunking. And it is clear that unmasking a deception is a modern ability that is easy to learn and helps us to find our way around in our complex world, especially when hiring or interviewing people or negotiations or administration are one of our own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at appreciating other people, arousing their interest and controlling their own emotions, and they feel intuitively how they are perceived by others.
Thanks to research, we know that extroverted people lie more often than introverted people, that men more often "self-oriented" lies than women, whose lies are more "orientated to others" - usually they want to protect the feelings of others - that married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are usually lies).
We also know that when a person is exposed as an evildoer, others feel less guilty about lying to that person.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, by observing that person’s normal behavior.
This is called baselining, the starting position.
It provides a reference point for later evaluation of changes.
Observe the attitude, the laughter, the voice quality of their subject.
You should know better when someone usually triples with their foot constantly, so they don’t blame them wrongly if they triple with their foot during a meeting.
Then pay attention to accumulations of conspicuous verbal and non-verbal behaviors.
Think of these accumulations as alarm bells that scream, not as evidence of decay.
People who are deceiving may starve when they try to remember their story, perhaps pointing their feet towards the door or leaning towards the exit, changing their position in significant ways, or showing a "relaxation after the hiring conversation", this deep, relaxing exhalation, and the change in attitude when all the hard questions are over.
Askers often falsely signal that a hiring interview is over, just to look for this relaxation after the hiring interview.
Also, pay attention to the language of your subject.
Scott Peterson's slip is famous when he used the past form when he claimed his dead wife was still alive and triggered a national search for her.
Deceptive people can also use a distancing language: "I had no sexual relationship with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or if you repeat a tricky question in general.
The most common verbal signs are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when answering a tricky question: "Well... to tell you the truth... as far as I know... to the best of my knowledge and conscience."
As a result, the answer becomes more perceptive than factual, which often causes the alarm bells to ring.
There is no magic tool to unmask lies, but you can learn skills that make unmasking possible.
Thanks to these skills, everyone is less likely to become a victim of scammers, both in private and professional life.
