The low temperatures in February not only caused millions of losses in agriculture, but also placed tight limits on the growth of the national economy and caused a general decline in economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first quarter. This is mainly due to the historical decline in agricultural development of 31.16 percent, which had a slowing effect on other economic sectors.
According to a report published by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development) on the impact of the frost, 582,000 hectares of agricultural land have been damaged, of which 78.03 percent have been completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent have been partially destroyed.
