Lower liquidity
The economics scientist Gerardo López Cervantes, dean of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the Autonomous University (UAS), comments that the policies of public institutions indirectly explain the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently seeing is an increase in unemployment that has to do with several factors, including loss of liquidity in the market as a result of the cuts in funding passed by legislation to combat money laundering in Congress, because for those who illegally accumulate dollars, it is not easy to let them work for themselves, invest them or use them for anything else," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment is also inherent in a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the country looking for work abroad, especially in the United States, has declined. This is due on the one hand to the problems of entry and on the other hand because it is difficult to find work there too. These people stay here and look for work here, which increases unemployment," he says.
Black-working
The analysis of the labor market in Sinaloa is even more serious when one considers the high proportion of black work, which according to INEGI includes 60.38 percent of employees in the country who work without paying into the social security funds.
Unemployment and black work are the lowest wages in Mexico, according to statistics from the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Security Institute) and the Secretaria del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Mexico’s government agency for labour and social welfare).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos until September, which is much less than the national average of 7375 pesos.
Decrease in ADI
In addition to declining economic activity and rising unemployment, the largest decline in foreign direct investment (FDI) in the last ten years was recorded in 2011. According to the Ministry of Economy (State Economic Authority), the ADI was $630,597 from January to June, representing a decline of 87.74 percent compared to the 5,143,312 dollars in the same period the previous year.
The Secretariat for Economic Development of the Government (Governmental Authority for Economic Development) has a total investment of 17,280,000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The debt
In the face of the economic crisis, the state government applied to the National Congress in July for a loan of 3,000,000,000 pesos to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities in order to reactivate the economy. The National Congress approved an amount of 200,600,000 pesos, but no positive impact of debt on any of the economic sectors in the country could be found until November.
Reactions
For the representatives of entrepreneurship, the first year of government made Mario López Valdé’s incapacity to rule obvious.
Miguel Loredo López, chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (Mexico’s state chamber of manufacturing industry), said that no effort was made in 2011 to harmonize the views of different sectors, including the state government.
"Economic activity in Sinaloa has been really very poor this year, hard work has to be done to regain the land lost this year and in 2012 we have to do twice as much. The efforts of all, and in particular the progress of the already well-coordinated government team, have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year hampered and slowed the country’s economic development.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the frost. One of the most important impacts is a slow economy that is not sufficiently in motion to produce an economic dynamic that could produce an acceptable flow of processes, products and services, which is why we will conclude the year well below our expectations," he said.
Redefining a vocation
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la Rep<0xC3><0xBA>blica Mexicana (Mexican business association) in Sinaloa, said that the state must be encouraged to engage in more dynamic productive activities.
