The quintet included Costa Rica on its tour to celebrate its 20th anniversary
"Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam says the band is prepared to give one of their best concerts at the National Stadium next Sunday.
They were expected to play for more than 20 years, but the band assured them that a dream would come true when they played in Costa Rica.
The bassist and co-founder of the group, Jeff Ament, who gave Viva an exclusive interview last week from Brazil, assured.
The band is in the South American part of their tour to celebrate their twentieth anniversary and on Sunday, the 20th, they make their only stop in Central America.
On this day, they will perform at the National Stadium from 7.30 pm with the band The X from Los Angeles and Las Robertas from Costa Rica.
You are reading an excerpt from the conversation, the complete copy of which can be found in the online edition of La Nación.
For your Costa Rican fans, a dream comes true when Pearl Jam plays in Costa Rica: Are you aware of what that means for your fans?
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream that comes true for us as well.
This is just the second time we’ve played in South and Central America, and so far it’s been great.
I have only been to Costa Rica for a holiday once. It is such a beautiful country that we are sure to stay there for a few more days.
It’s exciting for us to bring our music there.
I ask you this because the fans of the band are completely devoted, they experience the days before the concert.
What do you say to your most enthusiastic fans?
Thank you for standing by our side all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for having waited so long and we are sorry to have taken so long until we got here.
Some people even think that your concert will be the biggest show of the year.
Doesn’t that put a little pressure on your visit?
Some of the greatest shows we’ve put on in the last 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We played on a couple of gigantic shows in Sao Paulo and we hope they made us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
Really, we want to play there.
We love this country, we love surfing and we are passionate about the jungle, for which Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
Many of our friends are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo where the waves are just unimaginable.
My friends have always gone surfing to Costa Rica and Nicaragua. Together with Mexico, this is a great area to surf. In this way, about people who love surfing, we learned about it.
With a look at the tour you have offered gigantic shows with many songs.
What are your plans for the event in Costa Rica?
Since we have never played there, we also set no limits.
We will try to give the best possible show with many different songs. We want to play a few songs from each album and offer our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
Why? Why?
I think that’s partly because we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs. Everyone likes a different song, so the decision we’re going to play each time isn’t easy.
If we put two or three songs that we haven’t played for a long time into the repertoire, we can better maintain our concentration and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked these songs, otherwise they could be forgotten.
This makes the show more interesting for us and I think that’s why it’s also interesting for the audience.
With this tour, you will celebrate your twenty-year history.
When you look back, do you find it hard to believe in your success?
Yeah, totally.
First of all, I don’t think any of us ever imagined playing in a great rock band for more than 20 years, and that sounds like a dream.
We also continue to rely on this blessing and find it great to be able to make music together even now.
We love and love to make music.
We are lucky to be able to drive to the places in the world that we have always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't be better.
What did it mean for you to have participated actively in the birth of Grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of great bands.
We are good friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and abundantly unusual when a movement emerges from a group of friends.
Every now and then a band comes out of a city, but it’s unusual for five or ten groups to come out of the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on their tour. We are still happy to be friends with them all and we are honored to be part of this up-and-coming Seattle sound.
It’s also very unusual that a band like yours has stayed together with the same musicians for so long.
Yes, four of us have been playing together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) came to us 13 years ago, which alone is much longer than many bands survive.
First of all, I believe that we all appreciate that we are happy to be alive and we also take care of each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical paths have opened up that give each individual the freedom to experiment.
One trusts the other and their music. We couldn't be better.
Your relationship with fame has not always been easy, but on the other hand, thanks to your success, you have always been able to do what you wanted.
How do you find a balance?
The way we have grown has made it easier for us to find balance.
We make sure you’re not touring too often, because it’s too easy to fall for this game with huge crowds who love your music.
As long as you think that people have come because of the music, it reminds you that you have to pay attention to the music and what it has brought to life, without the need to be a famous rock star.
What memories do you have of your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote very good songs and it was great in the beginning.
We were a band for three years that had never released a record until Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
We were disappointed to have taken so long. We are still good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who built the band with us. When I hear a song or see photos, I think about what an incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh. It was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh together and talk about music and football and many other topics.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The domestic band Las Robertas is responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose the band for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos from several groups and we liked this band the best, so we are curious to see what Las Robertas can offer live. It will certainly be exciting.
Why do you always change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter when you play live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), I don't know.
He sings it, and I think he sings the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who influenced you as a bassist?
From so many+
Among the first to come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bass players I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge alive, even though it is no longer a fad?
I think we all don’t feel very connected to the word grunge.
When I think about it, I think of the bands I mentioned before, such as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came up at the same time. If they are still important today, I think it’s great because it’s worth listening to this music and bands like Mudhoney are now making better music than ever before.
At first her music was darker, now she is more positive.
Why? Why?
That’s interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the new album that might seem a bit lighthearted, but there are also other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, although they also have something positive about them.
The tears came to both of them when I heard Ed playing them. They're very dark songs.
I believe that when you get older and something traumatic has happened in your life – for example, when you lose a family member or a friend – it affects your artistic work and your music and these two songs clearly embody that for me.
But I also believe that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
