Fujimori returned to the hospital for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to examine the muscle loss of his legs, his family doctor said.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who served 25 years in prison for human rights violations during his reign (1990-2000), has several diseases, including tongue cancer, which has been operated on four times and is under control.
Alejandro Aguinaga, a member of Congress and his personal doctor, told television that Fujimori was being examined for three days at the Peruvian hospital Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neoplasticas to determine the reason for his pain and muscle loss in the lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that, in his opinion, Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons, but he did not want to do so because he considered him innocent.
He has been operated on four times for tongue cancer and he has lost 18 kilos of weight, with other diseases such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, hypertension and blood circulation problems in the legs, the doctor counted.
Fujimori has been in the National Directorate of Special Police Operations since September 2007.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the death squad of the Peruvian army, which was secretly active during his reign.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and consisting of several ministers and entrepreneurs, will start their visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calderón, which will be the highlight of his full schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the collective of Uruguayans living in Mexico, according to the Uruguayan president.
The meeting of the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara “is suitable for exchanging information on all policy areas between the two countries,” the South American country’s presidential office announced on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is seeking Calderón’s support for the incident with France when French Prime Minister Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 summit in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude those countries that still act as tax havens from the international community, which Uruguay rejected and prompted a request to its ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has chaired the G20, a group of the most powerful emerging and developed countries in the world, since November, and since January this year, there has been an agreement on exchanging tax information to avoid double taxation with the South American country.
In recent years, the Government of Uruguay has sought to accelerate the implementation of agreements on the exchange of tax information in order to be removed from the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD)'s "grey list" of countries that have not introduced all international standards for cooperation in tax matters.
At the business level, a free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay has been in place since 2004, which has contributed to a growing exchange of goods between the two countries.
