Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome announces details of the plane crash in which Secretary of State Francisco Blake and seven others were killed.
The Secretaria de Comunicaciones y Transportes - SCT (Secretariat of Communications and Transport in Mexico) informed that the results of the investigation of the accident in which the Secretary of Government Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people died, indicate that the helicopter with all its intact structure crashed directly against the ground without the pilot could have initiated an emergency landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that the pilot had confirmed before the launch that the weather conditions had been suitable for the flight.
"The fact that the propeller wing was in contact with trees at a height of 25 meters, with the helicopter losing the trunk, seems to indicate that the helicopter had had several ground contacts."
He also explained that the helicopter was built for 19 occupants, which is why it met all the requirements for the transport of personnel.
He also said that no helicopter parts were found during the investigations in the area where the machine had crashed.
"In the search, no aircraft parts were found elsewhere, the surcharge affected the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 passengers, which is why it met all the requirements for passenger transport.
The area has an incline of 7 to 30 degrees.
At present, it is a priority to get the results of the investigation as soon as possible, but they can take several months, maybe even a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Secretariat for Aircraft and Auxiliary Services in Mexico), assured that the helicopter had flown from the Estado Mayor Presidential at a speed of travel and the plane had fallen on a soft slope.
"This information reinforces the assumption that it was a normal flight operation at the time of the crash."
At a press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, identified six relevant points that should be taken into account in the investigation:
Sight flight:
In accordance with flight standards, it was a flight according to the rules of sight flight, which means that the crew should have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded suitable weather conditions at the start, and during the flight to the border area between Mexico City and the state of Mexico, some low-hanging clouds erupted.
Selected flight routes:
It is possible that the team had chosen a lower area with better views towards the Cuernavaca Valley because of the clouds.
Impact site:
The impact coordinates and the helicopter's last radar recordings are the same, and there may have been no loss of control over the aircraft or deviation from the flight route before the impact.
Dispersion of the remains of the aircraft in a limited area:
The information available to date suggests that the helicopter had hit from a straight and lateral direction.
The pattern of scattered aircraft remains suggests that the helicopter had hit the ground with its intact structure.
No evidence of fire or explosion:
The remains of the aircraft at the accident site do not indicate fire or explosion.
The latest results indicate several ground contacts.
In the field investigations, aircraft parts were found at an altitude of 9,200 feet above sea level, the terrain is downhill and has a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter probably broke.
Some information suggests that the helicopter may have had several ground contacts.
After a thorough search of an area beyond the locked area at the crash site, no scattered aircraft parts could be found, reinforcing the assumption that the intact aircraft structure had hit the ground.
MSS Announces a Research Protocol to Find the Gene for Obesity
The Social Security Institute of Mexico is leading a research project to find the gene for obesity in children and adolescents, supported by IPN specialists.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Social Insurance Institute of Mexico) announced that it is conducting a research project to discover the gene for obesity in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of obesity in childhood and youth" to find the genetic markers associated with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, head of the Medical Research and Biochemistry Unit at Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, explained that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers has been established.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students at the Instituto Nacional de Salud P<0xC3><0xBA>blica (INSP) and at the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) of the Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The public is invited to participate in the study. Interested people can come to the sports fields of the IMSS in the valley of Mexico, where tests with children and adolescents are carried out every Saturday from 8.00 a.m.
He stressed that the investigation began at the Cuauhtémoc sports field (in the west of the state of México) and has continued since October 8 at the Nezahualcóyolt sports field (in the east of the state of México).
When the target of 500 to 600 investigators is reached, the study will continue at the Independencia sports field (in the south of the capital district) and will be completed at the Morelos sports field (in the north of the capital district).
He explained that the aim of the study was to understand the factors and the role of genetics in connection with the development of obesity and the identification of risk factors of Mexican children and adolescents for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the World Diabetes Day, he said that the aim was to have three thousand children and adolescents aged six to 14 years with the consent and under the supervision of their parents fill out nutrition-related questionnaires.
They will also be asked questions about their physical activity and family history to control risk factors that could result in diabetes or kidney failure.
He further stated that on the mentioned Saturdays, the subjects were measured (weight, size, waist circumference), monitored their blood pressure and determined blood values such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (trying to identify genes related to childhood obesity).
Cruz López stressed that this study would be conducted in response to health care workers’ concern about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"The health surveys from 1999 and 2006 showed that in just under six years, the proportion of obese boys has increased by 77 percent and that of girls with obesity by 47 percent.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the population of Mexico differs from that of other peoples.
He stated that one Mexican was on average 65 percent Native American, 30 percent European, and 5 percent African, which is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
In general, he explained that the genetics of obesity are expressed in the inability to burn the excess energy (calories) taken from us, so that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the study participants would be in a comprehensive study of the children, which would determine whether they had a degree of obesity or obesity.
It would even investigate the occurrence of dark skin wrinkles in the neck and inner arm (acanthosis), which indicate the likelihood of metabolic disorders and pre-stage diabetes.
All information will be treated confidentially and communicated to the parents in writing by the doctors. The doctors will explain to the parents all measurement results and suggest lifestyle changes that are appropriate for the prevention of diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three basic factors that are responsible for overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: lack of exercise, that is, lack of exercise in everyday life, spending most of the day in front of the TV and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
The high calorie intake, that is, an increased consumption of sugary drinks and carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) together with a high fat and protein intake as well as the genetics, which is to be analyzed in this research project.
Asphalt from UNAM prevents potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University UNAM develops polymer-modified asphalts to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If we were to pay attention to the signs that come from the road surface, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 potholes when the rainy season breaks out in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (city area of the Valley of Mexico), said Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the University of UNAM, warning and assured that the number of potholes would be significantly affected and assured.
In his lecture "Technical Hitholes", which he gave on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, but which has greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behavior of the road surface and thus avoid the appearance of potholes.
He explained that asphalt - the heaviest part of petroleum - is a hydrocarbon compound, one part of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphaltenes - and the other part a low - the so-called malthenes.
The tensile strength of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180° C., at 120° C. it is very viscous and at 50° C. it is almost firm, while it becomes brittle at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in a day depending on weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," said the chemical engineer.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City mostly have a flexible road surface composed of six layers of material, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the top layers lies a wear layer of asphalt, which consists of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this wear layer has been bathed in asphalt.
If the vehicles move on it and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed," said the chemical engineer.
"Atop the wear layer," he said, "is laid out a final layer, the so-called support layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which has also been bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tires, they require greater mechanical force than the wear layer and it has to produce friction.
The one that receives and distributes the most forces from these road surfaces also requires a suitable thickness and the material from which it is made must be maintained.
Weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, especially water, he said, "because it significantly impairs the behavior of the wear layer.
When the terrain gets moist, water enters the layer and is difficult to exit again, causing all layers of the road surface to soften and as a result, the appearance of potholes.
When a percussion hole is created, he said, "the cover layer is first removed, while the wear layer is only affected afterwards, but the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that should be maintained at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) explained that the vehicle load is another important cause of the occurrence of potholes, so the thickness of each layer of the road surface must always be proportional to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is complied with to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there was still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which were already on the market in other countries, and with which the potholes could be repaired easily and without the use of high temperatures.
