Energy policy:
Facts should overcome dogmas
If there is an issue that cannot be addressed on the basis of short-term considerations or on the basis of emotions, this is certainly energy policy.
The availability and costs of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is reasonable to take an election meeting as an occasion to reflect on this issue and on the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will bear fruit only if it explores the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on this planet, demographic evolution is driving a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, so a huge proportion of the world’s population should not have to do without a vital element.
At the same time, it is necessary to mitigate the scarcity of fossil resources in order to continue to produce electricity consistently, without forgetting the compelling need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate, in order to combat climatic irregularities.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany continues to remain isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is not the case in Belgium, which is subjecting its decision to the need to find a substitute source, nor in Switzerland, which is just planning to build nuclear power plants of the last generation.
The United Kingdom, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name but a few, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
The United States, for its part, decided after Fukushima to add another unit to its park by recommissioning the Three Mile Island plant, which was shut down after the nuclear accident.
Even if the German model, which is oriented towards renewable energy sources, is occasionally set as a model, reality contradicts the discourse.
The election in Berlin will be reflected in the form of an increase in the price of electricity, an increased energy dependence on Russia, in particular, due to the increased use of imported gas, and an increase in CO2 emissions from gas and coal-fired power plants.
The totality of these unpleasant effects will be noticeable within a few months.
The case of Denmark gives reason for reflection.
On the one hand, Denmark is the European leader in terms of wind energy, from which it derives 30% of its electricity, on the other hand, the country is one of the strongest users of coal and gas, used alternately with wind energy; as a result, its CO2 emissions and its electricity price are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the corresponding European average.
Thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than our French households.
As the energy price in the globalised economy is a key role of competitiveness and a pledge of stability for industry on national soil, French companies have an advantage due to the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore result in a sharp increase in the price of energy, which would make the noble statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power an illusion.
Surveys have shown that this is a price that the vast majority of French people are just as unwilling to pay as it shows resistance to the principle of this energy source.
Let us bear in mind that the energy policy of our country has made it possible to build an industry with 125.00 direct and 410,000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export character, it brings a multitude of specialized small and medium-sized companies to the international markets and makes them creators of countless jobs.
Should France decide to phase out nuclear power, a majority of these SMEs would fall victim to it, and the annual 6 billion euros in investment goods and nuclear energy exports would shrink more and more.
Which electrician would hire an EPR designed to function for sixty years if the decline of its producer is preprogrammed?
In order to solve the energetic equation, one must admit that there is as little as a devil’s work a miracle means of generating electricity.
The low-carbon solutions developed by Areva for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy testify to the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a security authority that performs uncompromising and transparent controls on existing plants, such as the construction in Flamanville.
Their work teams, who have made a name for themselves because of their professionalism, are obsessed with the idea of safety.
Within 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious crashes.
Only one, in Three Mile Island, has occurred under normal operating conditions, so it went without consequences for humans and the environment.
In Chernobyl, the drama was evoked by reactor construction and inexcusable human failure.
In Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude, which caused the deaths of several tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn its lessons from this accident just as it did after the two preceding ones.
As a result of this approach and a cooperation between the security authorities of the French and German operators and designers of nuclear power plants, the EPR presents a draft that allows it to be resilient to such phenomena.
Since it is considered desirable among electrical engineers to build a nuclear power plant, a construction stop in Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the competition of Areva and EDF by allowing them free rein in the leadership position in the inevitable nuclear power development.
It is inevitable and legitimate to look for the best energy bouquet for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and party maneuvers dominate a debate that determines our country’s economic, social and financial situation as well.
