The immigration policy under Nicolas Sarkozy was criticized from many angles - overloading police, judicial and administrative bodies because of a policy subject to the figures, compatibility of this policy with the status of a "country of human rights", as France had called itself.
Recently, the harassment directed against foreign students by the authorities had shaped the weekly shows, the Minister of the Interior had casually announced (see Libération of May 23) that France "had not needed talents, masons or waiters from abroad".
But this policy has rarely been analysed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus on this issue between the right and the left.
From the right, the tone was struck by Jacques Chirac, who had declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed, including over 2 million immigrant workers, should not be a problem for a country", from the left, by Michel Rocard, who had explained in 1990, France "can not accept all the poverty in the world".
The only difference is the degree of generosity
The fear of the invasion of national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared from both right and left in 2005.
Both camps saw immigrants as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity that one is willing to admit to immigrants.
In his program, Francois Hollande confines himself to banalities that indicate partnership development allows us to solve our “migration problems”.
This notion of immigration as a burden, as a problem, can potentially affect the elections; however, it is costly economically.
As economics experts Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out to us in a recently published work summarizing the latest findings on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.), there is a broad consensus among specialists regarding the positive impact of immigrants’ jobs on economic growth.
Restricting immigration would detract from growth and harm the labour market situation.
The fears of the influence of migrants are based on the notion that they threaten to replace local workers, especially the less skilled, by putting pressure on their wages.
However, experience shows that immigrants are in fact much more complementary than the local wage-earners, as they mainly engage in occupations in sectors that are technically unspent at the workplace.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not irritate local wage workers, and more skilled immigrants work in dynamic sectors where training is not aligned with the labour supply.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there is a lack of anesthesiologists, this complementarity also has a positive effect on wages and the domestic labour market between locals and migrants.
Giovanni Peri calculated in this way that a 1% increase in the flood of immigrants would result in a related, long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity of ideas brought by immigrants is conducive to economic growth (a large proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute net to social systems, on average in European countries at about 1% of the total budget.
The World Labour Organization estimates, for example, that a person who immigrates to Germany at the age of 30 makes an average net contribution (income minus expenditure) of around 150,000 euros to the public budget over his lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to bring about the missing intersections "with the teeth" at the start of his mandate.
However, these teeth, which were intended to deter immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, now it remains to think through European democracy
Democracy is a valuable asset; it is also a delicate asset.
The European continent should be able to remember for itself who, after their invention in Athens more than two thousand years ago, had suffered the entire 20th century about the tragedies of the First World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Francos in Spain, Salazars in Portugal and the supreme in Greece.
Some had believed that it was sufficient to exercise the right to vote, in the most direct way possible, to see democracy once and for all overcome its enemies.
It has been known since Napoleon "the Little One" that it was a characteristic of the attitude.
The general right to vote, which is the necessary condition of democracy, is not a sufficient condition for this and can become just as well an "instrument of oppression" as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot put it at the time.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, separation and control of powers, an education, enlightenment, an economic and social spirit, a jurisprudence.
The crisis in Europe we are in is an economic crisis, but it is also a political and democratic crisis.
The change of mind of the Greek True-False-referendum would have had a dual enlightening character in this respect: on the one hand, that of the need for a powerful return of politics, on the other hand, but also that of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its inappropriateness.
This ambivalence should be considered outdated.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have shifted today, and that the Republican soldiers, or at least most of them, are no longer heading in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain to push for a success of the national referendum, which was organized according to needs and in the wrong order.
A vacancy for the European sole ruler or a blind-eyed leap into the void of nationalist retreat: a great choice for the citizen!
No, we want Hackebeil, but a collective task, out of full right, clarified and steady, an election and democracy, this time on a European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain and Portugal - we no longer know where to end the enumeration - because there is only one crisis and this is prevailing in Europe.
It is Europe as a whole that bows to the dictates of the markets and the rating agencies, which suffer from its powerlessness and lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is humiliated on an international level.
One is concerned about transfers of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe that is gradually losing its sovereignty, and thus every one of the nations associated with it.
The urgency is to return the leadership of the European project to the people's sovereignty.
Because it is all about whether Europeans can reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from markets and launch a future through investment.
The exit from the crisis has decisions on a conditional European level which cannot be taken without total democratic law without certainly leading us to ruin.
After this proposal has been fought for a long time by Jacques Delors and the Socialists, everyone today is pushing for European economic governance.
Agreed.
But imagining this without political integration and a stronger democracy - as it envisages the citizens - would be another folly and another dead end.
We must take on a new stage of European integration.
In order to create a republic in France, it was necessary to “create” republicans.
The revolution of interests alone could not suffice here.
This teaching remains valid.
We need to build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be achieved by creating a more politically democratic Europe, a truly European people's sovereignty.
We need Europeans to create Europe.
"Contactless" Chip Cards Become a Common Good
The world fair for chip cards opens its doors on Tuesday in Villepinte near Paris in an optimistic attitude.
According to Eurosmart, 2011 should actually end with an 11% increase in worldwide sales of microprocessor chips (EC cards, SIM card phones), with more than 6 billion units sold.
The most important segment is contactless technology, which enables payments in public transport or payment of purchases by simply holding the card to a reader.
Compared to the 320 million sold a year earlier, 460 million contactless chip cards are expected to be sold worldwide this year!
Its market share is expected to increase further in 2012 (580 million expected units) and represent over 10% of the global chip card market (6,925 million cards).
Europe is gaining ground in terms of contactless payment, after having been behind the Asia-Pacific region for a long time.
Some 26 million Visa cards are already equipped with this functionality, and 75,000 payment terminals accept it.
In France, the beginnings are rather modest: only 400,000 contactless visa cards have been distributed.
However, the consumer markets are steaming.
Carrefour has therefore issued 2.5 million contactless Pass MasterCards this year.
In order to move to higher speeds, it is now necessary for banks to equip their customers with these cards.
“Two large French financial institutions have committed themselves to systematically handing out contactless chip-equipped bank cards to their customers in the future,” said Gérard Nébouy, General Manager of Visa Europe France.
Banks test payment by mobile phone
However, this is only a first step on the way to the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
A small percentage of devices have so far been equipped with the NFC (Near Field Communication) technology necessary to carry out these transactions.
"They're late."
"But they should see a real upward trend at least next year."
"We expect to sell 80 to 120 million units worldwide in 2012," said Marc Bertin, Chairman of Eurosmart.
Banks are taking the initiative.
Crédit Agricole announced yesterday the start of a test run in Caen, which will run from December to next June.
The iPhones of some 200 customers and employees will be equipped with a capsule that allows contactless payment.
BPCE operates a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
Société Générale also announced yesterday that it was preparing to launch an offer that would allow its customers to make contactless payments via mobile phone.
