Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas transmission line, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is expected to supply gas to an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with brilliance and glory.
More than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended last Tuesday the inauguration of the new gas transmission line Nord Stream, which connects Russia and Germany directly below sea level.
The German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, the Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, the French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his counterpart Mark Rutte from the Netherlands have symbolically jointly turned the control of the valve that transports the Russian gas into the Western European network.
The new gas pipeline will deliver 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas per year through a first 1,224 km long pipeline connecting the St. Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania to Western Europe.
A second pipeline, which will allow a total supply of 55 billion cubic meters of gas - the equivalent of total French consumption - is expected to be completed by the end of 2012.
And the eventuality of the construction of a third line on the same route is already heard.
For Gazprom, the timely and punctual completion of this enormous building seems like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The North Stream pipeline will enable direct gas delivery to Germany, while avoiding any route through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) by land.
For this reason, these two countries are losing a little of their power: for them it is now becoming more difficult to put pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most engaged in the debate, was not afraid to compare the North Stream pipeline with a “new German-Soviet pact” in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the purpose of the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is extremely sensitive politically.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by advocating this Russian project.
However, this is at the expense of defusing European energy, as the project has broken a gap between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has managed to implement its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which have high gas consumption and whose gas reserves are declining.
“This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way,” Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out to what extent the major gas contracts are also important from the political and economic side.
All this explains the broad smile of the numerous Gazprom managers represented in Lubmin regarding the gas pipeline.
The construction of this gas transmission line is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater pipe is made of steel with concrete sheathing, which is intended to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at about 200 m depth.
During its construction, minefields dating from the Second World War had to be evaded.
"About hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect the fauna and flora.
The line is a long queue made of metal, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which is not interrupted over the entire length by anything: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers have refrained from this, as the Swedes were little prepared to see a Russian state company permanently settle at the level of their coasts.
"In the event of a breakdown, we close the gas outlet in less than a minute," Jens Müller said.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the gas transmission line escapes into the air.
This case, however, is considered by the designers to be very unlikely, as the weld seams were estimated to have a resistance of one leak per 100,000 years.
State monitoring of the gas transmission line is ensured by an underwater robot controlled from a marine vessel for external observation purposes, as well as by a device circulating inside the gas transmission line.
It has the shape of a cigar, with a diameter of one meter, is introduced into the interior of the pipeline and moved through the gas pressure.
After three full days of movement through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on any deformation of the metal upon arrival.
The gas transmission line was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo even the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is easily ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entry point and 100 bar at the exit point.
Five companies have joined forces to implement this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
In addition, the German companies E. ON and BASF are affiliated (each at 15.5%), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French company group GDF Suez (each at 9%).
These five companies have formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas transmission line.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom has then leased to this company the full capacity of its gas transport, on a twenty-year contract that can be extended.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the amount of gas that is actually transported is", explained Jens Müller.
The financing of gas pipeline construction was secured by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
Total labour costs for both pipelines should be €7.4 billion.
For GDF Suez, for example, the total investment amounted to 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders are reluctant to recover their expenses, as Gazprom bears the liability risk alone.
The gas pipeline comes to light on a sandy, pine-wooded coastal stretch near Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4.5-metre high valves form the gas outlet gates.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other parameters of the incoming gas before it is passed on to the German gas transmission lines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with one million cubic meters of Russian gas per hour.
At full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic meters per hour and 6 million in 2012.
